EQUINE HERPESVIRUS - NORTH AMERICA (04): CANADA (ONTARIO) HORSE
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: 20 Feb 2021
Source: Equus Magazine [edited]
https://equusmagazine.com/news/ehv-cases-ontario


Three facilities in the Canadian province of Ontario are now under quarantine due to the neurological form of equine herpes virus, type 1 (EHV-1).

In early February 2021, health authorities were alerted to an outbreak of EHV-1 on a farm in the Municipality of Halton. According to the Equine Disease Communication Center (EDCC), 2 horses were affected in the private facility. Both were euthanized following the sudden onset of severe incoordination and an inability to stand.

Most cases of equine herpesvirus-1 (EHV-1) infection cause only mild to moderate respiratory illness, but occasionally some lead to life-threatening neurological disease.

This week, the EDCC reported that 2 more farms went under quarantine. On one property, in the Regional Municipality of Peel, an 18-year-old gelding was euthanized after he developed neurological signs, including severe hind-limb incoordination and an inability to stand. The other property is home to a 7-year-old mare who is having difficulty urinating and is currently being treated.

EHV-1 most often causes mild-to-moderate respiratory illness (rhinopneumonitis), but the infection occasionally leads to the life-threatening neurological disease EHM. The mechanisms through which EHV-1 produces neurological disease are not yet understood. There is no vaccine specifically protecting against EHM, so biosecurity is a crucial part of prevention. EHV-1 spreads from horse to horse through nasal discharge or aerosol droplets. Humans can spread the virus via contaminated hands, clothing, and equipment.

To learn more about EHM and how you can protect your horse, see: https://equusmagazine.com/horse-care/prevent-ehm-in-horses..

